article.description:
Margo Dydek was busy, but she hardly seemed to
work up a sweat.
article.headline: Dydek scores, rebounds, defends ... and enjoys passing

images.name: Dydek_Margo 020630 inline
images.caption: Margo Dydek finished with 19 points, 13 rebounds, two blocks and two assists for Utah.

article.linkText: Dydek does it all in leading Utah past Cleveland
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Margo Dydek was busy, but she hardly seemed to
work up a sweat.

<photo1>

	   The Utah center scored 19 points, grabbed 13 rebounds and sparked a strong interior defense as the Starzz defeated the Cleveland
Rockers 79-62.

	   Dydek, a 7-foot-2 center from Poland, made eight of 14 shots from
the field, displaying a soft touch from the outside. Defensively,
she controlled the inside game and continually forced the smaller
Rockers to alter their shots and retreat to a perimeter game.

	   Cleveland missed all 11 of its 3-point attempts.

	   ''All of that is good, but the statistic that jumps out at me is
assists,'' Utah coach Candi Harvey said. ''We shared the ball
extremely well.''

	   Utah had 24 assists to the Rockers' eight.

	   Dydek spoke little about her own game, other than to say she
wanted to join in the passing.

	   ''They want me to score. I can do that, but I like to pass,''
she said. ''The all-around game wins.''

	   Natalie Williams and Marie Ferdinand each scored 17 points for
Utah (9-4). They combined to make 14 of 18 shots from the field.
The Starzz missed their final five shots and finished at 59 percent
from the field.

	   ''You see those numbers and obviously they were getting quality
shots,'' Rockers coach Dan Hughes said. ''We never really got into
what we wanted to do defensively. Dydek presents problems with her
size and Ferdinand is very quick and so tough in transition.''

	   Ann Wauters scored 20 points to lead Cleveland (6-7), which had
a three-game winning streak snapped. Most of her points came inside
after Dydek left with 6:40 to play and the Starzz ahead 67-53.

	   ''Margo makes the game so different,'' Wauters said. ''You don't
want to change your shots, but you change. And every player pays so
much attention to her, you turn your head and somebody else beats
you.''

	   Chasity Melvin added 18 points for Cleveland before fouling out
with 2:31 to play.

	   The Rockers were without starting point guard Jennifer Rizzotti,
who sprained her right ankle in the second half of a victory at New
York on Friday night.

	   ''Jen tried everything she could to get ready, but 15 minutes
before the game, it was obviously a no-go,'' Hughes said.

	   The Rockers appeared sluggish from the start of their fifth game
in eight nights. Cleveland missed its first six shots, while the
Starzz hit their first five to take a 12-0 lead.

	   ''I don't know if we were mentally ready,'' Melvin said. ''You
can't take a break in this league.''

	   Wauters scored eight points in a run that tied the score at 25.

	   Utah then finished the first half on a 13-4 spurt to lead at the
break 38-29.

	   The Starzz maintained their lead throughout the second half
despite a total of 21 turnovers.

	   ''They tried to double-team Margo, but she still shot over
them,'' Williams said. ''They really did not have an answer for our
inside game.''
